      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is undeniably a more rigorous legal method because it anchors judicial interpretation in historical evidence, which provides a fixed standard for analysis. Living constitutionalism, on the other hand, is inherently subjective, allowing judges to inject their contemporary political views into the law without external constraint. Therefore, when assessing legal soundness, the commitment to verifiable historical meaning makes originalism the demonstrably more disciplined approach.",
      "source": "target",
