    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if originalism is the more disciplined and rigorous way to do it, doesn't that basically mean any ruling that goes against that historical reading is just judicial activism? it seems like if the law isn't being applied according to the actual text and history, then the court is basically just acting as a legislature instead of a court.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, from a strict originalist perspective, any ruling that significantly diverges from the understood meaning of the text at the time of its ratification is fundamentally an act of judicial activism. When a court begins to rewrite the law based on modern social preferences rather than historical understanding, it is effectively usurping the role of the democratically elected legislature. This is precisely why originalists argue that such decisions are illegitimate exercises of power, not legitimate interpretations of the Constitution.",
      "source": "target",
